</div>\n|<div>33</div><hr /><div>19</div>\n|<div>14</div><hr /><div>8</div>\n|<div>6th of 9</div><hr /><div>4th of 6</div>\n|-\n | 1899-1900 || [[Kent Football League (1894-1959)|Kent League]] || 19 || 5 || 2 || 12 || 24 || 49 || 12 || 10th of 11\n|-\n | 1898-99 || {{sort|2|[[Kent Football League (1894-1959)|Kent League]]}}<hr /><div>{{sort|3|South Suburban League Division One}}</div>\n|<div>24</div><hr /><div>13</div>\n|<div>8</div><hr /><div>12</div>\n|<div>8</div><hr /><div>0</div>\n|<div>8</div><hr /><div>1</div>\n|<div>47</div><hr /><div>51</div>\n|<div>58</div><hr /><div>17</div>\n|<div>24</div><hr /><div>24</div>\n|<div>9th of 13</div><hr /><div>1st of 8</div>\n|-\n | 1897-98 || {{sort|2|[[Kent Football League (1894-1959)|Kent League Division One]]}}<hr /><div>{{sort|3|South Suburban League Division One}}</div>\n|<div>14</div><hr /><div>10</div>\n|<div>3</div><hr /><div>5</div>\n|<div>3</div><hr /><div>2</div>\n|<div>8</div><hr /><div>3</div>\n|<div>26</div><hr /><div>22</div>\n|<div>36</div><hr /><div>14</div>\n|<div>9</div><hr /><div>12</div>\n|<div>7th of 8</div><hr /><div>2nd of 6</div>\n|-\n | 1896-97 || {{sort|2|[[Kent Football League (1894-1959)|Kent League Division One]]}}<hr /><div>{{sort|3|South London League Division One}}</div>\n|<div>16</div><hr /><div>16</div>\n|<div>6</div><hr /><div>9</div>\n|<div>1</div><hr /><div>3</div>\n|<div>9</div><hr /><div>4</div>\n|<div>44</div><hr /><div>42</div>\n|<div>37</div><hr /><div>18</div>\n|<div>13</div><hr /><div>21</div>\n|<div>7th of 9</div><hr /><div>3rd of 9</div>\n|-\n | 1895-96 || [[Kent Football League (1894-1959)|Kent League Division Two]] || 16 || 12 || 0 || 4 || 56 || 21 || 24 || 3rd of 9 [[Promotion and relegation|Promoted]]\n|-\n | [[1894-95 Kent Football League|1894-95]] || [[Kent Football League (1894-1959)|Kent League Division Two]] || 16 || 10 || 2 || 4 || 48 || 25 || 22 || 3rd of 9\n|-\n|}\n\n==Grounds==\nCray Wanderers currently play their home games at Hayes Lane, Bromley.\n\nCray started playing football at Star Lane, now a cemetery. After playing at numerous other grounds, Cray played at Grassmeade from 1954 to 1973, after which they moved to Oxford Road.  Unfortunately for the club, in 1998 the Kent League ruled that clubs must have floodlighting.  As Cray were unable to have lights installed, they were forced to move out and share the Hayes Lane ground of [[Bromley F.C.|Bromley]], although their reserve and youth teams continued to play at the former ground until 2011, when it was taken over by [[Sporting Club Thamesmead F.C.|Seven Acre Sports & Sidcup]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Club History (brief)| publisher = Sporting Club Thamesmead F.C. | url = http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/sportingclubthamesmeadfc/a/a-brief-history-of-sporting-club-thamesmead-fc-31729.html | accessdate = 2016-11-16}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cray Wanderers at Oxford Road in 1997.jpg|thumb|right|Cray Wanderers at Oxford Road in 1997.]]\n\nIn the summer of 2008, Cray announced plans to move to a new stadium near Orpington by 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chairman has grounds for optimism ahead of play-offs |publisher=Kentishfootball |date=28 April 2008 |url=http://www.kentishfootball.co.uk/mambo/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3051&Itemid=38 |accessdate=2008-07-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904013001/http://www.kentishfootball.co.uk/mambo/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3051&Itemid=38 |archivedate=4 September 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jenkins faces Cup Final selection dilemma |publisher=Kentishfootball |date=13 July 2008 |url=http://kentishfootball.co.uk/mambo/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3288&Itemid=38 |accessdate=2008-07-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904013006/http://kentishfootball.co.uk/mambo/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3288&Itemid=38 |archivedate=4 September 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>  Official plans published on the club's official website on 18 February 2009 confirmed that the new ground at Sandy Lane would be open by 2014, for the 2014\u201315 season, subject to planning consent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cray Stop Wandering After 40 Years! |publisher=Official Website |date=18 February 2009 |url=http://www.craywands.co.uk/component/content/article/102-nowander |accessdate=2009-02-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223074138/http://www.craywands.co.uk/component/content/article/102-nowander |archivedate=23 February 2009 }}</ref>  The stadium, which is proposed to be part of a new \"Sports Village-like complex\" is set to be eco-friendly and be built to an initial [[Football Conference|Conference]] standard.\n\nThe bid was rejected unanimously, by all councillors on Bromley Council's Development Control Committee on Thursday 20 September 2012. This was for a number of reasons, but mainly because the Club was hoping to build a Football League sized stadium, using the profits from building nearly 200 houses and a large hotel on Green Belt land.\n\nIn the debate on the application, which was opposed by the Police and the GLA as well as other bodies, it was clear that Councillors were supportative of a proposal to relocate Cray Wanderers to a new home in St. Pauls Cray, but not to the building of houses, a hotel and another swimming pool, given that LA Leisure already have a swimming pool opposite the site, in order to fund it.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\nOn 3 October 2014, Cray Wanderers signed a conditional contract to purchase Flamingo Park Sports Centre in St Paul\u2019s Cray on the A20 Sidcup bypass. The club had an 18-month period to obtain planning consent from Bromley Council for a new sporting community hub, featuring a new multi-sport stadium with a spectator capacity of 1,300. This was achieved in April 2016, when the Council approved the proposal.<ref>{{cite web | title = Bromley Council approve planning permission for Flamingo Park | publisher = Official website | date = 19 April 2016 | url = http://www.cray-wanderers.com/bromley-council-approve-planning-approval/  | accessdate = 2016-04-30}}</ref> There was disappointment when the application was later refused by the [[Mayor of London]] and a revised set of plans were being prepared in 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title = Stadium updates | publisher = Official website | date = 13 April 2017 | url = http://www.cray-wanderers.com/stadium-updates/  | accessdate = 2017-05-17}}</ref>. These were finally approved in November 2018, with hopes that the club will be able to move in for the start of the 2021&ndash;22 season <ref>{{cite web | title = Cray Wanderers get Mayor's backing for new stadium at Flamingo Park | publisher = News Shopper | date = 27 November 2018 | url = https://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/17258428.cray-wanderers-get-mayors-backing-for-new-stadium-at-flamingo-park/  | accessdate = 2019-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Academy==\nThe Cray Wanderers Academy, based at [[Coopers School]], [[Chislehurst]], was established in January 2009 by representatives of the club (Gary Hillman and Darren Anslow) and school (Oliver Hobbs and Shirley Puxty).\n\nIt provided the opportunity of full-time training and the prospect of a future sporting career, whilst also offering an educational route.\n\nThe Academy is for 16- to 18-year-olds and competed in the Isthmian Youth League from the 2009\u201310 season, finishing second.\n\nIn its first season it already showed signs of success, with youngster [[George Porter (footballer)|George Porter]] breaking into the senior first team in the Academy's first season, impressing to the extent that he was signed by professional club [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] at the end of the season. Several other players have made first team appearances during the first season.\n\nIt was decided at the beginning of 2016 that this arrangement with Coopers School would come to an end. The club are looking at establishing another Academy setup in the next couple of years.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Honours==\n*[[Isthmian League]] Division One\n**Winners (South East): [[2018\u201319 Isthmian League|2018\u201319]]\n**Runners-up (South): [[2008-09 Isthmian League|2008\u201309]]\n**Play-off Winners (South): [[2008-09 Isthmian League|2008\u201309]]\n*[[Kent Football League|Kent League]]: 1901\u201302, 1980\u201381, 2002\u201303, 2003\u201304\n**Runners Up: 1979\u201380, 1990\u201391\n*[[London League (football)|London League]]: 1956\u201357, 1957\u201358\n**Runners Up: 1953\u201354, 1954\u201355\n*[[Aetolian League (football)|Aetolian League]]: 1962\u201363\n*[[Greater London League]]: 1965-66\n*[[Metropolitan-London League]]: 1974-75\n*[[London Spartan League]]: 1976\u201377, 1977\u201378\n*[[Kent Senior Trophy]]: 1992-92, 2003\u201304\n*[[Kent Amateur Cup]]: 1930\u201331, 1962\u201363, 1963\u201364, 1964\u201365\n*Best league performance: 9th in [[Isthmian League Premier Division]], [[2010\u201311 Isthmian League|2010\u201311]], [[2011\u201312 Isthmian League|2011\u201312]]\n*Best [[FA Cup]] performance: 4th qualifying round, 2005\u201306\n*Best [[FA Trophy]] performance: 2nd round (equivalent of current 3rd qualifying round), 2004\u201305. 3rd qualifying round, 2005\u201306, 2006\u201307, 2008\u201309, 2012\u201313, 2014\u201315, 2017\u201318\n*Best [[FA Vase]] performance: Quarter-finals, 1979\u201380, 2003\u201304<ref>{{fchd|name=Cray Wanderers|id=CRAYW}}</ref>\n*Best [[Kent Senior Cup]] performance: Final, 1900\u201301, 2007\u201308\n\n==Current squad==\n<ref>[https://www.cray-wanderers.com/teams/first-team/ First team] Cray Wanderers F.C.</ref>\n{{fs start}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=GK|name=Lewis Carey}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=GK|name=Grant Hall}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Tom Carlse}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Jay Leader}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Mitchell Nelson}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Geofrey Okwonko}}\n{{fs player|no=|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=Joe Vines|other=player-assistant manage