99\n| nationalteam1  = [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany U-21]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2014\u20132015\n| managerclubs1 = [[1. FC Saarbr\u00fccken]] (youth)<ref>[http://www.fupa.net/spieler/martin-forkel-26640.html Profile on Fupa]</ref>\n| manageryears2 = 2014\u20132015\n| managerclubs2 = [[1. FC Saarbr\u00fccken II]] (playing manager)<ref>[http://www.fupa.net/spieler/martin-forkel-26640.html Profile on Fupa]</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fupa.net/berichte/bernd-eichmann-kein-fcs-trainer-mehr-215237.html | title = Bernd Eichmann kein FCS-Trainer mehr | language = German | publisher = fupa.net | accessdate = 13 October 2013}}</ref>\n| manageryears3 = 2015\u20132016\n| managerclubs3 = [[1. FC Saarbr\u00fccken]] U19<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sr-online.de/sronline/sport/sportwelt/fcs_u23_abmeldung100.html | title = 1. FC Saarbr\u00fccken meldet U23 ab | language = German | publisher = sr-online.de | accessdate = 22 April 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150621233351/http://www.sr-online.de/sronline/sport/sportwelt/fcs_u23_abmeldung100.html | archive-date = 21 June 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wochenspiegelonline.de/content/nachrichten/integration/article/u19-mario-baric-uebernimmt-fuer-martin-forkel/ | title = U19: Mario Baric \u00fcbernimmt f\u00fcr Martin Forkel | language = German | publisher = wochenspiegelonline.de | accessdate = 1 June 2016}}</ref>\n| manageryears4 = 2015\n| managerclubs4 = [[1. FC Saarbr\u00fccken]] (caretaker)<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/3liga/startseite/629330/artikel_saarbruecken-trennt-sich-von-trainer-kilic.html | title = Saarbr\u00fccken trennt sich von Trainer Kilic | language = German | publisher = kicker.de | accessdate = 20 June 2015}}</ref>\n| manageryears5 = 2016\u20132017\n| managerclubs5 = [[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]] (caretaker)\n| manageryears6 = 2018\u20132019\n| managerclubs6 = [[Ho Chi Minh City FC|Ho Chi Minh City]]\n| manageryears7 = 2019\n| managerclubs7 = [[Esteghlal F.C.|Esteghlal]] (assistant)\n}}\n'''Martin Forkel''' (born 22 July 1979) is a German [[Association football|football]] manager and former [[Defender (association football)|defender]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/3liga/vereine/3-liga/2011-12/1-fc-saarbruecken-106/22027/spieler_martin-forkel.html | title = Forkel, Martin | language = German | publisher = kicker.de | accessdate = 2 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Youth career===\nForkel was born in [[Coburg]]. He played as a youth for two clubs in his hometown, [[Viktoria DJK Coburg]] and [[VfB Coburg]], before joining [[TSV Vestenbergsgreuth]]. TSV merged with [[SpVgg F\u00fcrth]] in 1996, forming [[SpVgg Greuther F\u00fcrth]], with whom Forkel would make his breakthrough in the professional game.\n\n===Southern Germany===\nForkel made one appearance for [[SpVgg Greuther F\u00fcrth]], as a substitute for [[Arie van Lent]] in a 3\u20131 win over [[FSV Mainz]] in the [[2. Bundesliga]] in December 1998. He was released by the club at the end of the 1998\u201399 season, signing for [[Borussia Fulda]] of the [[Regionalliga S\u00fcd (1994\u20132012)|Regionalliga S\u00fcd]]. Fulda were relegated in Forkel's only season with the club, finishing 17th, but he was to stay at the third tier, signing for [[Wacker Burghausen]] in July 2000.\n\nIn Forkel's first season with Burghausen, the club battled against relegation, but were promoted as champions in 2001\u201302, with Forkel and ever-present. He would go on to play for the club for four seasons in the 2. Bundesliga, achieving a mid-table finish each time, before leaving to join [[TuS Koblenz]] in July 2006.\n\n===Western Germany===\nForkel made his debut for [[TuS Koblenz]] on the opening day of the 2006\u201307 season, as a substitute for [[R\u00fcdiger Ziehl]] in a 2\u20131 defeat against [[MSV Duisburg]]. As at Burghausen, he would play for four seasons in the [[2. Bundesliga]], although his appearances were more restricted, and his time at Koblenz ended with the club being relegated to the [[3. Liga]] in 2010.\n\nForkel then joined another 3. Liga club, [[1. FC Saarbr\u00fccken]], where he would spend the next two seasons as a regular in the first team. He was released by the club in 2012, and spent a year with [[Borussia Neunkirchen]] of the [[Oberliga Rheinland-Pfalz/Saar]]. In July 2013 he returned to Saarbr\u00fccken, originally to play for [[1. FC Saarbr\u00fccken II|their reserve team]], but after coach [[J\u00fcrgen Luginger]] was replaced with [[Milan \u0160a\u0161i\u0107]] he was brought back into the first-team fold. He made his second debut for the club in September 2013 as a substitute for [[Philipp Hoffmann (footballer)|Philipp Hoffmann]] in a 1\u20130 defeat to [[SV Darmstadt 98]], and remained a first-team regular until the end of the season, which saw Saarbr\u00fccken relegated. Forkel then left the club for a second time.\n\n===International career===\nForkel was in the [[Germany national under-20 football team|Germany]] squad for the [[1999 FIFA World Youth Championship]], and made six appearances for the [[Germany national under-21 football team|under-21 team]] that same year.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Fussballdaten|forkelmartin|Martin Forkel}}\n\n{{1. FC Saarbr\u00fccken managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Forkel, Martin}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:SpVgg Greuther F\u00fcrth players]]\n[[Category:SV Wacker Burghausen players]]\n[[Category:TuS Koblenz players]]\n[[Category:1. FC Saarbr\u00fccken players]]\n[[Category:Borussia Neunkirchen players]]\n[[Category:2. Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:3. Liga players]]\