{"title_page": "Will Patton", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2008}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        =\n| caption      = Patton on the set of ''The List''\n| birth_name   = William Rankin Patton\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1954|6|14}}\n| birth_place  = [[Charleston, South Carolina]], U.S.\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| other_names  =\n| nationality  = American\n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = 1979\u2013present\n| website      =\n| partner      =\n}}\n'''William Rankin Patton''' (born June 14, 1954) is an American actor and audiobook narrator. He starred as [[List of Falling Skies characters#Captain Dan Weaver|Colonel Dan Weaver]] in the [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] [[science fiction]] series ''[[Falling Skies]]''. He also appeared in films such as ''[[Remember the Titans]]'', ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]'', ''[[Gone in 60 Seconds (2000 film)|Gone in 60 Seconds]]'' and ''[[The Punisher (2004 film)|The Punisher]]''. He appeared opposite [[Kevin Costner]] in two films: ''[[No Way Out (1987 film)|No Way Out]]'' (1987) and ''[[The Postman (film)|The Postman]]'' (1997). Patton's father, Bill Patton, was a playwright and acting/directing instructor. Patton has been in many films, starting in 1981. He has done many television appearances as well, starting in 1982 and he has done a great deal of voice work with audio books. He won two [[Obie Awards]] for best actor in [[Sam Shepard]]'s play ''[[Fool for Love (play)|Fool for Love]]'' and the Public Theater production of ''What Did He See?''.\n\n==Early life==\nPatton was born in [[Charleston, South Carolina]], the eldest of three children. His father is Bill Patton, a playwright and acting/directing instructor who was a [[Lutheran]] [[Religious minister|minister]] and served as a chaplain at [[Duke University]].<ref name=semi>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/05/movies/film-emerging-as-a-leading-man-of-supporting-actors.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=FILM; Emerging as a Leading Man of Supporting Actors |first=Justine |last=Elias |date=July 5, 1998 |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |page=9 |access-date=11 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hamptons.com/The-Arts/Top-Stories/10762/Bill-Patton-Returns-To-The-Hamptons-With-A-New.html |title=Bill Patton Returns To The Hamptons With A New Play |location=Bridgehampton, NY |work=Hamptons.com |access-date=May 16, 2012 |date=7 May 2010 |first=Douglas MacKaye |last=Harrington}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myharcum.com/s/1044/index.aspx?sid=1044&pgid=693&gid=1&cid=1327&ecid=1327 |work=[[Harcum College]] |title=Bill Patton One-Act Play |access-date=May 16, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714142800/http://www.myharcum.com/s/1044/index.aspx?sid=1044&pgid=693&gid=1&cid=1327&ecid=1327 |archive-date=14 July 2011}}</ref> Patton was raised on a farm, where his parents ran a [[foster care|foster home]] for wayward teenagers.<ref name=semi/> He attended the [[North Carolina School of the Arts]] in [[Winston-Salem]] and [[The Actors' Studio]] in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\n==Career==\nPatton won two [[Obie Award]]s for best actor for his performances in [[Sam Shepard]]'s play ''Fool for Love'' and the [[Public Theater]] production of ''What Did He See?''. He portrayed the evil antagonist in ''[[Desperately Seeking Susan]]'', and had a significant role in ''[[No Way Out (1987 film)|No Way Out]]'', his first major film. He was nominated for the [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actor (Film)|Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his portrayal of General Bethlehem in ''[[The Postman (film)|The Postman]]''. He also  portrayed [[Coach (sport)|coach]] [[Bill Yoast]] in ''[[Remember the Titans]]'' and FBI agent [[Melvin Purvis]] in the 1991 made-for-television film ''[[Dillinger (1991 film)|Dillinger]]'', before an acclaimed supporting actor performance in ''[[Armageddon]]''. Patton provided the voice for the audio version of ''[[The Assault on Reason]]'' by [[Al Gore]], as well as the role of Alan Wilson on the TV show ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]''. He has also recorded the audio version for 22 books written by best-selling mystery writer [[James Lee Burke]].  Patton plays the character of Sam Conroy in the film ''[[American Violet]]''.\n\nFrom 2011 to 2015, he starred as [[List of Falling Skies characters#Colonel Dan Weaver|Colonel Weaver]] in the [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] sci-fi television series ''[[Falling Skies]]'', executive-produced by [[Steven Spielberg]].\n\nIn 2019, Patton portrayed Avery Sunderland in the [[DC Universe (streaming service)]] TV series, ''[[Swamp Thing (2019 TV series)]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1983\n| ''Variety''\n| Mark\n|\n|-\n| ''King Blank''\n| Bar Customer\n|\n|-\n|  ''[[Silkwood]]''\n| Joe\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1985\n| ''[[The Beniker Gang]]''\n| Forest Ranger\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Desperately Seeking Susan]]''\n| Wayne Nolan\n|\n|-\n| ''[[After Hours (film)|After Hours]]''\n| Horst\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1986\n| ''Chinese Boxes''\n| Lang Marsh\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Belizaire the Cajun]]''\n| Matthew Perry\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[No Way Out (1987 film)|No Way Out]]''\n| Scott Pritchard\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1988\n|  ''[[Wildfire (1988 film)|Wildfire]]''\n| Mike\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Stars and Bars (1988 film)|Stars and Bars]]''\n| Duane Gage\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Signs of Life (1989 film)|Signs of Life]]''\n| Mr. Coughlin\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1990\n| ''[[Everybody Wins (film)|Everybody Wins]]''\n| Jerry\n|\n|-\n| ''[[A Shock to the System (1990 film)|A Shock to the System]]''\n| Lt. Laker\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Bright Angel]]''\n| Woody\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1991\n| ''[[The Rapture (1991 film)|The Rapture]]''\n| Deputy Foster\n|\n|-\n|  ''[[Cold Heaven (film)|Cold Heaven]]''\n| Father Niles\n|