e Tascioni\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Shots Fired]]''\n| Sheriff Daniel Platt\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Swamp Thing (2019 TV series)|Swamp Thing]]''\n| Avery Sunderland<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/swamp-thing-will-patton-cast-avery-sunderland-dc-universe-series-1202496341/|title=\u2018Swamp Thing\u2019: Will Patton Cast As Avery Sunderland In DC Universe Series|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 5, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n| {{TBA}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Voice work==\n\n===Audio books===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Title\n! Author\n! Year\n|-\n| ''[[Tales of Ordinary Madness]]'' || [[Charles Bukowski]] || 2017\n|-\n|''Call Down The Hawk''\n|[[Maggie Stiefvater]]\n|2019\n|-\n| ''[[The Outsider (King novel)|The Outsider]]'' || [[Stephen King]] || 2018\n|-\n| ''Robicheaux'' || [[James Lee Burke]] || 2018\n|-\n| ''[[The Mist (novella)|The Mist]]'' || Stephen King || 2017\n|-\n|''[[Killers of the Flower Moon]]''\n|[[David Grann]]\n|2017\n|-\n| ''[[End of Watch (novel)|End of Watch]]'' || Stephen King || 2016\n|-\n| ''The Raven King'' || Maggie Stiefvater || 2016\n|-\n| ''House of the Rising Sun'' || James Lee Burke || 2015\n|-\n| ''[[Finders Keepers (King novel)|Finders Keepers]]'' || Stephen King || 2015\n|-\n| ''Blue Lily, Lily Blue'' || Maggie Stiefvater || 2014\n|-\n| ''[[Mr. Mercedes]]'' || Stephen King || 2014\n|-\n| ''Doctor Sleep'' || Stephen King || 2013\n|-\n| ''The Dream Thieves'' || Maggie Stiefvater || 2013\n|-\n| ''The Son'' || [[Philipp Meyer]] || 2013\n|-\n| ''My Cross to Bear'' || [[Gregg Allman]] || 2012\n|-\n| ''The Raven Boys'' || Maggie Stiefvater || 2012\n|-\n| ''Creole Belle'' || James Lee Burke || 2012\n|-\n| ''[[Deliverance (novel)|Deliverance]]'' || [[James Dickey]] || 2011\n|-\n| ''Feast Day of Fools'' || James Lee Burke || 2011\n|-\n| ''The Glass Rainbow'' || James Lee Burke || 2010\n|-\n| ''[[Alas, Babylon]]'' || [[Pat Frank]] || 2010\n|-\n| ''[[Light in August]]'' || [[William Faulkner]] || 2010\n|-\n| ''[[Jesus' Son]]'' || [[Denis Johnson]] || 2009\n|-\n| ''Swan Peak'' || James Lee Burke || 2008\n|-\n| ''[[On the Road]]'' || [[Jack Kerouac]] || 2007\n|-\n| ''[[The Tin Roof Blowdown]]'' || James Lee Burke || 2007\n|-\n| ''[[The Assault on Reason]]'' || [[Al Gore]] || 2007\n|-\n| ''[[Fine Just the Way It Is: Wyoming Stories 3]]'' || [[Annie Proulx]] || 2008\n|-\n| ''[[Tree of Smoke]]'' || Denis Johnson || 2007\n|-\n| ''Last Car to Elysian Fields'' || James Lee Burke || 2007\n|-\n| ''[[Thirteen Moons (novel)|Thirteen Moons]]'' || [[Charles Frazier]] || 2006\n|-\n| ''Pegasus Descending'' || James Lee Burke || 2006\n|-\n| ''Crusader's Cross'' || James Lee Burke || 2006\n|-\n| ''Jolie Blon's Bounce'' || James Lee Burke || 2006\n|-\n| ''The Thomas Berryman Number'' || [[James Patterson]] || 2006\n|-\n| ''[[To Have and Have Not]]'' || [[Ernest Hemingway]] || 2006\n|-\n| ''A Dave Robicheaux Audio Collection'' || James Lee Burke || 2006\n|-\n| ''[[When Zachary Beaver Came to Town]]'' || [[Kimberly Willis Holt]] || 2006\n|-\n| ''[[Cosmopolis (novel)|Cosmopolis]]'' || [[Don DeLillo]] || 2005\n|-\n| ''In the Moon of Red Ponies'' || James Lee Burke || 2004\n|-\n| ''Cimarron Rose'' || James Lee Burke || 2004\n|-\n| ''White Doves at Morning'' || James Lee Burke ||2003\n|-\n| ''Bitterroot'' || James Lee Burke || 2001\n|-\n| ''Cadillac Jukebox'' || James Lee Burke || 2001\n|-\n| ''Purple Cane Road'' || James Lee Burke || 2000\n|-\n| ''[[Boone's Lick]]'' || [[Larry McMurtry]] || 2000\n|-\n| ''Burning Angel'' || James Lee Burke || 1999\n|-\n| ''[[Heaven's Prisoners]]'' || James Lee Burke || 1999\n|-\n| ''[[Heartwood]]'' || James Lee Burke || 1999\n|-\n| ''[[Primal Fear (novel)|Primal Fear]]'' || [[William Diehl]] || 1999\n|-\n| ''Dixie City Jam'' || James Lee Burke || 1999\n|-\n| ''A Stained White Radiance'' || James Lee Burke || 1998\n|-\n| ''Sunset Limited'' || James Lee Burke || 1998\n|-\n| ''[[The Sea-Wolf]]'' || [[Jack London]] || 1997\n|-\n| ''[[Dead Man's Walk]]'' || Larry McMurtry || 1996\n|-\n| ''[[Dirty White Boys]]'' || [[Stephen Hunter]] || 1995\n|-\n| ''[[The Water Is Wide (book)|The Water Is Wide]]'' || [[Pat Conroy]] || 1995\n|-\n| ''[[The Fermata]]'' || [[Nicholson Baker]] || 1995\n|-\n| ''[[Gump and Co.]]'' || [[Winston Groom]] || 1995\n|-\n| ''Gone South'' || [[Robert R. McCammon]] || 1994\n|-\n| ''Lila \u2013 An Inquiry into Morals'' || [[Robert M. Pirsig]] || 1991\n|-\n| ''The Lost Get-Back Boogie'' || James Lee Burke || 1986\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0001599}}\n*{{iobdb name|10559}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patton, Will}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Obie Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Actors from Charleston, South Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2008}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        =\n| caption      = Patton on the set of ''The List''\n| birth_name   = William Rankin Patton\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1954|6|14}}\n| birth_place  = [[Charleston, South Carolina]], U.S.\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| other_names  =\n| nationality  = American\n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = 1979\u2013present\n| website      =\n| partner      =\n}}\n'''William Rankin Patton''' (born June 14, 1954) is an American actor and audiobook narrator. He starred as [[List of Falling Skies characters#Captain Dan Weaver|Colonel Dan Weaver]] in the [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] [[science fiction]] series ''[[Falling Skies]]''. He also appeared in films such as ''[[Remember the Titans]]'', ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]'', ''[[Gone in 60 Seconds (2000 film)|Gone in 60 Seconds]]'' and ''[[The Punisher (2004 film)|The Punisher]]''. He appeared opposite [[Kevin Costner]] in two films: ''[[No Way Out (1987 film)|No Way Out]]'' (1987) and ''[[The Postman (film)|The Postman]]'' (1997). Patton's father, Bill Patton, was a playwright and acting/directing instructor. Patton has been in many films, starting in 1981. He has done many television appearances as well, starting in 1982 and he has done a great deal of voice work with audio books. He won two [[Obie Awards]] for best actor in [[Sam Shepard]]'s play ''[[Fool for Love (play)|Fool for Love]]'' and the Public Theater production of ''What Did He See?''.\n\n==Early life==\nPatton was born in [[Charleston, South Carolina]], the eldest of three children. His father is Bill Patton, a playwright and acting/directing instructor who was a [[Lutheran]] [[Religious minister|minister]] and served as a chaplain at [[Duke University]].<ref name=semi>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/05/movies/film-emerging-as-a-leading-man-of-supporting-actors.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=FILM; Emerging as a Leading Man of Supporting Actors |first=Justine |last=Elias |date=July 5, 1998 |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |page=9 |access-date=11 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hamptons.com/The-Arts/Top-Stories/10762/Bill-Patton-Returns-To-The-Hamptons-With-A-New.html |title=Bill Patton Returns To The Hamptons With A New Play |location=Bridgehampton, NY |work=Hamptons.com |access-date=May 16, 2012 |date=7 May 2010 |first=Douglas MacKaye |last=Harrington}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myharcum.com/s/1044/index.aspx?sid=1044&pgid=693&gid=1&cid=1327&ecid=1327 |work=[[Harcum College]] |title=Bill Patton One-Act Play |access-date=May 16, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714142800/http://www.myharcum.com/s/1044/index.aspx?sid=1044&pgid=693&gid=1&cid=1327&ecid=1327 |archive-date=14 July 2011}}</ref> Patton was raised on a farm, where his parents ran a [[foster care|foster home]] for wayward teenagers.<ref name=semi/> He attended the [[North Carolina School of the Arts]] in [[Winston-Salem]] and [[The Actors' Studio]] in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\n==Career==\nPatton won two [[Obie Award]]s for best actor for his performances in [[Sam Shepard]]'s play ''Fool for Love'' and the [[Public Theater]] production of ''What Did He See?''. He portrayed the evil antagonist in ''[[Desperately Seeking Susan]]'', and had a significant role in ''[[No Way Out (1987 film)|No Way Out]]'', his first major film. He was nominated for the [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actor (Film)|Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his portrayal of General Bethlehem in ''[[The Postman (film)|The Postman]]''. He also  portrayed [[Coach (sport)|coach]] [[Bill Yoast]] in ''[[Remember the Titans]]'' and FBI agent [[Melvin Purvis]] in the 1991 made-for-television film ''[[Dillinger]]'', before an acclaimed supporting actor performance in ''[[Armageddon]]''. Patton provided the voice for the audio version of ''[[The Assault on Reason]]'' by [[Al Gore]], as well as the role of Alan Wilson on the TV show ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]''. He has also recorded the audio version for 22 books written by best-selling mystery writer [[James Lee Burke]].  Patton plays the character of Sam Conroy in the film ''[[American Violet]]''.\n\nFrom 2011 to 2015, he starred as [[List of Falling Skies characters#Colonel Dan Weaver|Colonel Weaver]] in the [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] sci-fi television series ''[[Falling Skies]]'', executive-produced by [[Steven Spielberg]].\n\nIn 2019, Patton portrayed Avery Sunderland in the [[DC Universe (streaming service)]] TV series, ''[[Swamp Thing (2019 TV series)]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1983\n| ''Variety''\n| Mark\n|\n|-\n| ''King Blank''\n| Bar Customer\n|\n|-\n|  ''[[Silkwood]]''\n| Joe\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1985\n| ''[[The Beniker Gang]]''\n| Forest Ranger\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Desperately Seeking Susan]]''\n| Wayne Nolan\n|\n|-\n| ''[[After Hours (film)|After Hours]]''\n| Horst\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1986\n| ''Chinese Boxes''\n| Lang Marsh\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Belizaire the Cajun]]''\n| Matthew Perry\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[No Way Out (1987 film)|No Way Out]]''\n| Scott Pritchard\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1988\n|  ''[[Wildfire (1988 film)|Wildfire]]''\n| Mike\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Stars and Bars (1988 film)|Stars and Bars]]''\n| Duane Gage\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Signs of Life (1989 film)|Signs of Life]]''\n| Mr. Coughlin\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1990\n| ''[[Everybody Wins (film)|Everybody Wins]]''\n| Jerry\n|\n|-\n| ''[[A Shock to the System (1990 film)|A Shock to the System]]''\n| Lt. Laker\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Bright Angel]]''\n| Woody\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1991\n| ''[[The Rapture (1991 film)|The Rapture]]''\n| Deputy Foster\n|\n|-\n|  ''[[Cold Heaven (film)|Cold Heaven]]''\n| Father Niles\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[In the Soup]]''\n| Skippy\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1993\n| ''The Paint Job''\n| Wesley\n|\n|-\n| ''Midnight Edition''\n| Jack Travers\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Romeo Is Bleeding]]''\n| Martie\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | 1994\n| ''Tollbooth''\n| Dash Pepper\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Natural Causes (1994 film)|Natural Causes]]''\n| Michael Murphy\n|\n|-\n| ''Judicial Consent''\n| Alan Warwick\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Client (1994 film)|The Client]]''\n| Sergeant Hardy\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Puppet Masters (film)|The Puppet Masters]]''\n| Dr. Graves\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Copycat (film)|Copycat]]''\n| Nicoletti\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1996\n| ''Plain Pleasures''\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Spitfire Grill]]''\n| Nahum Goddard\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Fled]]''\n| Det. Matthew 'Gib' Gibson\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 1997\n| ''[[Inventing the Abbotts]]''\n| Lloyd Abbott\n|\n|-\n| ''Hounddogg''\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[This World, Then the Fireworks]]''\n| Lt. Morgan\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Postman (film)|The Postman]]''\n| General Bethlehem\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3| 1998\n| ''[[O.K. Garage]]''\n| Sean\n|\n|-\n